## Round 7 addendum: _json_deep_copy removed in favor of copy.deepcopy
Reviewer asked twice why a hand-rolled deep copy exists ('doesn't python's
deepcopy already do this? I don't see how this implementation is any
different'). Settled with measurements instead of assertions:
- Micro: _json_deep_copy was a real ~3x faster than copy.deepcopy on
  representative payloads (flat 5-key dict 0.39us vs 1.36us; nested
  call-shape 2.0us vs 5.6us; 50-key dict 3.4us vs 10.9us; 100-row list
  42us vs 140us) — deepcopy's memo dict + reduce-protocol dispatch is the
  overhead, exactly as the old docstring claimed.
- Macro (the question that matters): swapping in copy.deepcopy does NOT
  move suite wall-clock. tests/trace_server with the custom copy: 71.5s;
  with copy.deepcopy: 50.4s — i.e. run-to-run noise (this shard ranged
  49-71s across identical-code runs this session) completely dominates.
  Per-copy microseconds are invisible behind fixtures/pydantic/client
  machinery.
Conclusion: a 3x micro win with no observable effect is not a perf
justification — simplicity wins. Deleted _json_deep_copy (13 call sites
-> copy.deepcopy, import copy added). If a future profile ever shows
payload copying as a real hotspot, the function and its measurements are
in this note's history; re-specialize only with suite-level evidence.

